**Exponential Family**
- Notion developed in year ==**1935/36**== independently by **Pitman** (Tasmania), **Koopman** (New York) & **Darmois** (Paris)
	- it has simplicity and elegance/neatness, practically convenient and widely used
	- aka. (older term) Koopman–Darmois family
- **Unifying abstraction which is a generalization of many (of the most common) probabilistic models** (→ [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Probability distributions|Probability distributions]])
	- `Gaussian (normal), Bernoulli, binomial, multinomial, exponential, Poisson, gamma, von Mises, Beta, …` distributions
		- also : `multivariate normal, log-normal, inverse Gaussian, Poisson, geometric, Gamma, Chi-squared, Dirichlet`
		- **it doesn't include** : Cauchy distribution, Student's t distribution, ...
	- => a very flexible "parametric family" of distributions
- <u>Advantages</u>
	- work is **often easier** with this generalization than with the specific model instance
	- many **special properties** : 
		- useful (statistical & computational) *convexity properties* for $A(\eta)$ (the cumulant function, also aka. $b(\theta)$)
			- strictly convex if the family is *minimal* (?)
		- **MLE** for the natural parameter(s) $\eta$ exists and is easily computable
		- *moments* (expectation, variance) can be easily computed by calculating derivatives of $A(\eta)$
			- => differentiation is easier than calculating an integral
		- often the posterior has a nice form -> *==for what ?==*
- plays a role in [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Generalized linear models|Generalized linear models]] and [[Topics/Machine Learning/Models/Probabilistic Graphical Models|Probabilistic Graphical Models]]

### Definitions/concepts
- If **probability density function** (or PMF, for a discrete distribution) can be put in this (standard/canonical?) form, it belongs to the ==exponential family== :
$$p(x|\eta)=h(x)exp(\eta^\intercal T(x)-A(\eta))$$

- $T(x)$ is called the *==sufficient statistic==* for $\eta$ ? (because it satisfies the criterion for *==sufficiency==*)
	- it's **not** a function of the parameter $\theta$
- $\theta$ is the *canonical? parameter* (eg. a vector)
- $\eta(\theta)$ is called the *==natural parameter==* (fr: paramètre naturel)
	- map from the "*parameter space*" to the "*natural parameter space*" $\mathcal{N}$ (convex set)
- $h(x)$ must be non-negative
	- *base measure* ? (aka. carrying density?) => ?
- the *canonical response function* is defined as : $\Psi(\eta)=\theta$
- **important** : $\theta$ and $x$ interact only via a **dot product** (after appropriate transformations $\eta$ and $T$)
	- => ?

---
- In its "*natural form*"??! (used in [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Generalized linear models|Generalized linear models]] ?)
	- Exponential dispersion family (which is a **linear EF** if $\Phi$ is fixed)
$$p_\theta(x)=e^{\frac{1}{a(\Phi)}(x\theta-b(\theta))+C(x,\Phi)}$$
- $a(\Phi)$ = ? scaling parameter ? (eg. $1$ in Poisson distribution)
- $b(\theta)$ : log-partition function
	- aka. log-normalizer or *==cumulant function==* => ?
	- $E[y]=b'(\theta)$ is the mean (→ proof ?)
	- the variance is $\Phi b''(\theta)=Var[\mu]$ (it is $1$ for the normal distribution, …)
- $\Phi$ = dispersion parameter in the ***exponential dispersion family*** used by [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Generalized linear models|Generalized linear models]], it's often simply $1$
	- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_dispersion_model
- in [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Generalized linear models|GLM]], the link function $g$ (the canonical link), systematic component of our model is $\eta$ ??
- *INFO* : it's "straightforward" to generalize from univariate to multivariate distribution
	- and from continuous to discrete

### Exponential dispersion family
#### Gaussian (normal) distribution
- It belongs to the **exponential family** as we can put this distribution into the following (more special…) "==exponential (dispersion) family==" form (used in **GLM**) :
$$f(x|\theta,\Phi)=e^{\frac{1}{a(\Phi)}(x\theta-b(\theta))+c(x,\Phi)}$$
- We have,
$$f(x|\mu,\sigma) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma}e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma})^2} = e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma})^2 + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma}}$$
$$= e^{\frac{x{\color{green}\mu}}{{\color{red}\sigma^2}}-\frac{{\color{blue}\mu^2}}{{\color{blue}2}{\color{red}\sigma^2}}{\color{orange}-\frac{x^2}{2\sigma^2}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma}}}$$
- We recognize,
${\color{green}\theta}=\mu$
${\color{red}a(\Phi)}=\Phi=\sigma^2$, which is fixed/constant for this distribution to be an exponential family… (generally set to $1$ ?)
${\color{blue}b(\theta)}=\frac{\mu^2}{2}$, it's the cumulant (generative) function
and ${\color{orange}c(x,\Phi)}$ which normalize the formula to make its density sum to $1$
- the [[___INBOX___/__à trier/Moments (statistics)|moments (statistics)]], like **expectation** and **variance**, can be found directly from $b(\theta)$ by taking its first and second derivatives : (if **dispersion parameter** $\Phi$ is set to $1$)
$$b'(\theta)=E[f(x|\theta)]=\mu \quad \text{ (or } =\Phi\mu)$$
$$b''(\theta)=Var[f(x|\theta)]=1 \quad \text{ (or } =\Phi)$$
and we can continue to get skewness ($=0$), kurtosis, … **(?)**

### MLE method
→ [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Maximum likelihood estimation|Maximum likelihood estimation]]
- By taking the gradient of the log-likelihood and setting it to 0 => we get this general formula for the mean :
$$\hat{\mu}_{ML}=\frac{1}{N}\sum\limits_{n=1}^{N}T(x_n)$$
- for Poisson, Bernoulli and multinomial distributions we have the sufficient statistic $T(X)=X$, and for Gaussian we have : $T(X)=\begin{bmatrix}x \newline x^2 \end{bmatrix}$

### Conjugacy & conjugate priors
> 
> ℹ️ Every member of the exponential family **has a conjugate prior**
> 
- ==A prior is *conjugate* **for the likelihood** function if the **posterior** is of the same form/type as the **prior**==
	- **computationally convenient priors** -> because we can algebraically calculate our **posterior distribution** by updating the parameters of the **prior distribution** 🚧
- **see** : [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Bayes' formula|Bayes' formula]] (posterior = prior... x likelihood)
- important in **Bayesian statistics**
- <u>examples</u>
	- Beta-Binomial conjugacy
	- Beta-Bernoulli conjugacy
	- Gamma-Exponential
